                &lt;span class=&quot;comment-copy&quot;&gt;&lt;code&gt;git update-index --assume-unchanged &amp;lt;path&amp;gt; &lt;/code&gt; will cause git to ignore changes in the specified path(s), regardless of &lt;code&gt;.gitignore&lt;/code&gt;. If you pull from a remote and that remote has changes to this path, git will fail the merge with a conflict and you will need to merge manually.  &lt;code&gt;git rm --cached &amp;lt;path&amp;gt; &lt;/code&gt; will cause git to stop tracking that path. If you do not add the path to &lt;code&gt;.gitignore&lt;/code&gt; you will see the path in future &lt;code&gt;git status&lt;/code&gt;.  The first option has less noise in the git commit history and allows changes to the &quot;ignored&quot; file to be distributed in the future.&lt;/span&gt;

