                &lt;span class=&quot;comment-copy&quot;&gt;@RomainValeri: Git will fail (gracefully) in case it needs to modify this file in the index e.g. when merging in a commit; thus, in case the assumed-untracked file is changed upstream, you will need to handle the situation manually.&lt;a href=&quot;http://git-scm.com/docs/git-update-index&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer&quot;&gt;git-scm.com/docs/git-update-index&lt;/a&gt;. You commit to: (1) backup the file out of the tree; (2) reset the a.-u. bit; (3) reset the file to its original content &lt;code&gt;git checkout -- file&lt;/code&gt;; (4) git pull or merge, which will now succeed; (5) copy the file back and examine changes; (6) set the a.-u. bit again. That&apos;s a definition of PITA in my book, but YMMV. :)&lt;/span&gt;

